What's going on
The 127.0.0.53 you see is not CoreDNS — it's systemd-resolved's stub listener running on the node itself. Image pulls are performed by containerd at the node level, so they use the node's DNS, not Kubernetes CoreDNS. The chain is:
containerd (image pull) → /etc/resolv.conf → 127.0.0.53 (systemd-resolved) → ??? upstream
Bottlerocket gathers the name servers from the DHCP lease Bottlerocket by default, but there are known issues where systemd-resolved doesn't properly forward to the DNS servers in your DHCP option set — particularly when using systemd-networkd/resolved, AWS sends domain names using DHCP option 15 in a non-standard way GitHub which can cause parsing issues.
The fix: explicitly set DNS in Bottlerocket user data
Rather than relying on DHCP option set propagation, explicitly configure DNS servers in your Bottlerocket bootstrap_extra_args. In your terraform-aws-eks module config:
hcleks_managed_node_groups = {
  bottlerocket_fips = {
    ami_type = "BOTTLEROCKET_x86_64_FIPS"
    platform = "bottlerocket"

    bootstrap_extra_args = <<-EOT
      [settings.dns]
      name-servers = ["10.0.0.2", "your.custom.dns.ip"]
      search-list = ["your-domain.internal", "us-east-1.compute.internal"]
    EOT
  }
}
Replace 10.0.0.2 with your VPC's .2 resolver (VPC CIDR base + 2), and add whatever custom DNS servers you have in your DHCP option set. The search-list should match the domain names from your DHCP option set.
Debugging steps
If you want to confirm the issue first, SSM into a Bottlerocket node via the control container and check what systemd-resolved is actually using:
bash# Enter the admin container
enter-admin-container

# Check what systemd-resolved thinks its upstream DNS servers are
resolvectl status

# Or check the resolv.conf that containerd sees
cat /run/systemd/resolve/resolv.conf
If resolvectl status shows no upstream DNS servers, or shows the wrong ones, that confirms the DHCP option set isn't being picked up properly — and the explicit [settings.dns] in user data is the right fix.
Why this happens specifically with Bottlerocket FIPS
Bottlerocket FIPS variants use newer systemd-networkd based networking (as opposed to the older wicked based stack on some variants). Variants using systemd-networkd (*-k8s-1.28-* and newer) use /run/systemd/resolve/resolv.conf Bottlerocket rather than the traditional /etc/resolv.conf. The systemd-networkd DHCP client is stricter about RFC compliance, and AWS's DHCP option set implementation does not conform to RFC2132 — it sends multiple domain names packed into DHCP Option 15 instead of using DHCP Option 119 DevOps, which causes issues with systemd's DHCP client.
The explicit [settings.dns] in user data bypasses the DHCP negotiation entirely for DNS settings, which is the most reliable approach.
